>Mina Shirakawa: In a manner of speaking, I am the daughter of a company president (laughs). My father built the company in his lifetime, and I think he was thinking of having me, his eldest daughter, take over if possible. Unlike my younger sister, I was raised quite strictly, and was sent to a private, all-girls' school for middle and high school. But school didn't suit me at all. ...... Everyone had the same hair color and the same skirt length, and I did what the teachers told me to do, and every day was boring.

>Shirakawa: I originally wanted to be a singer, but all the business cards I received were from gravure agencies, so I took it as a sign that I was wanted in this genre and jumped into the world of gravure. However, it was really hard for me to wear a swimsuit in front of people during my first shoot, and I cried during my first DVD shoot. ......

>Shirakawa: I became more and more interested in going overseas. I thought, "In order to compete overseas, I should do something different. I was seriously thinking about moving to the U.S. and doing the rounds when I got the Corona disaster, and I felt that going to the U.S. was not going to happen for a few years. When it comes to transmitting from Japan to the rest of the world, Stardom is probably the closest thing across the ocean. I decided that I had to compete here. So when the U.S. tour came to fruition in October, it really felt like a dream, and I wasn't nervous because it didn't feel too real.

>Lady C. I have always loved making clothes for stuffed animals, so I went to a university where I could study clothing design. So I can do everything from Western-style dressmaking to Japanese-style dressmaking and pattern making. When I was a pro wrestling fan, I made several costumes at the request of wrestlers, and even after I debuted, I basically made my own ring costumes.
>I had always wanted to work making and designing clothes, but when I took a teaching class in college, I really enjoyed it. Many people think of home economics as a traditional course with cooking classes and Western-style dressmaking, but it's actually different now. We talk about pensions, credit card systems, and even retirement, and the content is designed to make students imagine their life plans. For me, who had studied mainly clothing, it was a very rewarding job, as I learned a lot myself.

>Lady C. I would get the last train home every day, go home from there to make printouts for my classes, and get up first thing in the morning the next day to ....... I was always sleep deprived, and I had to drink nutritional drinks to get through the day. It was difficult to devise a lesson that would keep the students occupied. But I knew that if I gave good lessons, the students' reactions would be different. Because they were close in age, they treated me like a big sister, and I think I got along well with the students. I really enjoyed the work itself.
>I was able to work with the students in a very friendly manner. ...... However, there is a lot to do, such as preparing for classes, club activities, committee meetings, and school events. Not only was it physically demanding, but it also made me mentally unstable, and there were times when I would suddenly burst into tears in the school bathroom and couldn't stop.

posts.com:
Prior to Giulia, my only meaningful experience with an Italian was Super Mario. I grew up playing Super Mario World and Super Mario 64 on the SNES and N64, respectively. I made great memories, learning the different power ups, using trial and error to determine the best strategies to get through the levels, and eventually beating the games. Those moments gave me a sense of accomplishment, and I always appreciated the journey it took to arrive at those feelings.

Fast forward to 2021, when I committed to watching Stardom, the first person to catch my eye was Giulia. She had blonde, straight hair at shoulder length at the time. She had a very different look from the rest of the roster, I thought. Soon enough, I’d learn that she was Italian.

In the time I‘ve been able to watch Giulia, I’ve seen her act cocky as the White Belt Champion, become humbled after losing her belt and getting her head shaved bald, lean into some comedy with Syuri (the Afro entrance and dance when AliKaba faced AphroditE is one of my fondest comedy moments of 2021!), bring in two new wrestlers to Stardom who have made big impressions in 2022 in MIRAI and Thekla, steal a wrestler from Kozuen, lose a wrestler to Kozuen, have an emotional one on one match against her former kohai Suzu, and finally get her win back against Tam by defeating her in the finals of this year’s 5 Star GP.

Giulia has taken my Stardom-watching experience on an emotional roller coaster. She’s the Super Mario of my adult life. As Giulia prepares to capture the Red Belt Championship to end the year, allow me to borrow a quote from Mario: “Let’s a-go!”

>Julia: Because I am half-Japanese, I get noticed even if I don't want to be. It was the same in Japan and also in Italy. I once stayed with relatives in Italy with the intention of living there permanently, but I was harassed because "my mother is Japanese," and I ended up returning to Japan after one year. I thought that people try to exclude those who are different from themselves. Of course, not all people are like that, but it's silly.

>Julia: I worked as a manager at my parents' restaurant and stayed in the restaurant industry for a long time after that. After school, I would take a short nap, go to work, work until about 5:00 a.m., take another nap, and then go to school during the day. It was like that every day.
>At the time, I was living in a 70-year-old, 40,000-yen apartment in Shin Nakano, and the electricity and water would occasionally stop. I will never forget the sense of accomplishment I felt when I finished paying all the tuition fees. I studied hard at the school and enjoyed special makeup and hair and makeup itself very much, but I felt that maybe this was not the job for me, that maybe I wanted to be in front of people rather than working behind the scenes. When I think about it now, it turned out to be a year like a hobby that I spent a lot of money on (laughs). A few months after graduating from vocational school, I joined a wrestling circle, and here I am today.

>Julia: I watched a match accompanied by a customer from a cabaret club, and I was hooked! I had always had an interest in pro wrestling. I remember watching WWE matches on TV when I was little. Sasha Vs Bayley is rated slightly better on cagematch. It's also from a time when the average standard for women's matches was a bit lower. The other high profile women's WWE matches: Asuka Vs Ember Moon and Charles Vs Becky are rated lower there. Britt Baker Vs Thunder Rosa is also rated lower than this.

Haven't t watched Sasha Vs Bayley for a while but my general feeling is that match and Shida Vs Hayter were achieving different things: Sasha and Bayley were carefully built for a while, were the last two "horsewomen" in NXT, and that match was the big end of an era payoff where Bayley finally won. Here Shida had suffered neglectful booking for a while, then built up a little, but also recently beaten by Toni Storm, so needed to be reestablished within the match as a serious contender. So my feeling is Sasha Vs Bayley was probably had a hotter crowd at the start, while Shida Vs Hayter had to work to really get the crowd. You could hear the crowd switch from just being on Hayter's side to 50/50 during the first 5 minutes.
